@startuml Qsix_Policy_Bias_Feedback_Loop
title Q6 Policy Bias Feedback Loop - Why Evasion Dominates Collection

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam activity {
  BackgroundColor White
  BorderColor Black
  ArrowColor Black
}

start

:Hunter improves through self-play;
:Opponent pool fills with stronger Hunters;
:Pellet attempts become riskier;

if (Expected value of collection > evasion?) then (yes)
  :Krishna attempts collection;
  :Replay buffer receives collect transitions;
  :Collect behavior improves;
else (no)
  :Krishna chooses safer evasion;
  :Episodes become long timeouts or low-pellet survival;
  :Replay buffer fills with evasion-heavy transitions;
  :Q-values reinforce survival and distance management;
  :Collection attempts become rarer;
endif

:Single policy head receives conflicting gradients\nmove toward pellet vs move away from Hunter;
:Evasion becomes the stable local optimum;

if (Phase 3 enabled?) then (GOP + CHER)
  :Gated network separates evade and collect heads;
  :CHER injects safe-collect counterfactuals;
  :Hierarchical pool preserves easy opponents;
  if (Live reward still favors evasion?) then (yes)
    :CHER dependency remains high;
    :Pellet contact improves but wins stay rare;
  else (no)
    :Collection becomes internally rational;
    :CHER injections decline over time;
    :Krishna learns robust collect-while-evading policy;
  endif
else (Phase 2)
  :Bimodal collapse persists;
endif

stop

legend
  Desired v6 signal:
  - CHER dependency falls
  - real pellet collection rises
  - wins increase against frozen evaluation Hunters
  - gate adapts to tactical context without collapse
endlegend

@enduml

